een making button blankets and bentwood boxes with clan crest designs, hosting feasts for hundreds of people, and composing and choreographing new songs and dances in the service of repatriation. The book comes to understand how shared experiences of sewing, weaving, dancing, cooking and feasting lead to the Haida notion of “respect,” the creation of kinship and collective memory, and the production of a cultural archive.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aHaida IndiansxKinshipzBritish ColumbiazHaida Gwaii. 0aHaida IndiansxMaterial culturezBritish ColumbiazHaida Gwaii. 0aHaida IndianszBritish ColumbiazHaida GwaiixAntiquities. 0aHaida IndianszBritish ColumbiazHaida GwaiixEthnic identity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266606140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442666061423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442666061.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles